"""
MKT Context Commentary — Galatians chapters 4–6
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-galatians-4-6.py
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

GALATIANS = {
  "4": {
    "1": '<p>The analogy of the heir under guardianship draws on Roman law of the tutela (guardianship for minors). Under Roman law, a minor who inherited property was placed under the legal control of a <em>tutor</em> (guardian) who administered the estate until the heir reached majority (typically 14 for males, 12 for females; or later ages for full property rights). During this period, the heir had no practical difference from a slave with respect to controlling the estate, though legally the heir was the owner. Paul uses this familiar legal institution to describe Israel\'s condition under the law: owners by covenant but controlled by the law\'s custodianship until the appointed time of maturity.</p>',
    "2": '<p>The <em>epitropos</em> (guardian, manager) and <em>oikonomos</em> (household steward, administrator) were distinct roles in Roman household administration. The <em>epitropos</em> was the legal guardian appointed by the father\'s will or by a court; the <em>oikonomos</em> managed the daily affairs of the estate. The combination suggests comprehensive oversight: both the legal guardianship and the practical administration of the minor\'s life were under appointed authorities until the father\'s predetermined time. The phrase "the time set by the father" (<em>hē prothesmia tou patros</em>) is a Roman legal term for the date specified in the will or by the testator for the heir\'s coming-of-age.</p>',
    "3": '<p>The "elemental forces of the world" (<em>stoicheia tou kosmou</em>) is one of the most debated phrases in Galatians. The term <em>stoicheia</em> (literally: things in a row, elements) had multiple uses in Greek: (a) the letters of the alphabet; (b) the basic elements of the physical world (earth, water, fire, air); (c) the celestial bodies and the calendar forces tied to them; (d) angelic/demonic beings who governed the cosmic order. In Galatians, Paul uses it for the powers that governed both Jewish religion (law-keeping, calendar observance) and Gentile religion (pagan festivals and their associated powers) — the common denominator being their contrast with the freedom of the Spirit in Christ.</p>',
    "4": '<p>"When the fullness of time had come" (<em>to plērōma tou chronou</em>) invokes the Jewish concept of God\'s appointed time for eschatological action. The rabbis spoke of the "end-time" as a divinely predetermined moment; Daniel\'s "seventy weeks" (Dan 9:24-27) and Qumran\'s periodization of history reflect similar ideas. The "fullness of time" for Paul is not merely historical coincidence but divine appointment: the Roman <em>Pax Romana</em>, the Mediterranean koine Greek linguistic unity, the Jewish diaspora\'s network of synagogues, and the long preparatory work of the OT all converge in the moment God sends his Son. <em>Gennōmenon ek gynaikos</em> (born of a woman) echoes the Suffering Servant\'s being "born of a woman" (Job 14:1; Sir 10:18) and simply affirms genuine human birth.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The double purpose of the Incarnation in v5 — "to redeem those under the law so that we might receive adoption as sons" (<em>huiothesian apolabōmen</em>) — uses the Roman legal institution of adoption (<em>adoptio</em> or <em>adrogatio</em>). Under Roman law, adoption transferred a person fully from one family to another, with all new rights and obligations; the adopted person had no fewer rights than natural children. The adopted child received the father\'s name, his <em>gens</em> (clan), and his inheritance rights. Paul\'s term <em>huiothesia</em> (son-placing) reflects this legal-cultural background: believers are given the full legal status of sons/children in God\'s household, not second-class or conditional membership.</p>',
    "6": '<p>The Spirit of the Son crying "Abba, Father" in the believer\'s heart (cf. Rom 8:15) preserves the Aramaic prayer-word used by Jesus himself (Mark 14:36). The bilingual formula (<em>Abba ho patēr</em> = Abba, Father) in both Galatians and Romans suggests it was a fixed liturgical expression in early Christian worship — a prayer-word that crossed the Aramaic-Greek linguistic boundary and was retained in both languages simultaneously. Its preservation in the Greek-speaking churches of Galatia and Rome demonstrates that the earliest Aramaic-speaking Palestinian community\'s prayer practice was transmitted across linguistic and cultural boundaries as a mark of authentic spiritual life.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The transition from slave to son to heir captures the entire movement of salvation history in three stages. In Roman social terms: a slave had no legal personhood, no property rights, no inheritance; a son had legal personhood and inheritance rights; an heir was the son who actually received the estate. The movement in Paul\'s argument mirrors the Roman legal process: Israel under the law was in the condition of managed minority; the coming of the Son and the Spirit of the Son elevates believers to full sonship with inheritance rights. The "heir through God" (<em>klēronomos dia theou</em>) emphasizes that the inheritance is given by God, not achieved by the heir.</p>',
    "8": '<p>"When you did not know God, you were enslaved to those that by nature are not gods" — Paul addresses the Galatians\' Gentile background. In Roman Galatia (located in central Anatolia), the major cults included the Great Mother (Cybele/Kybele) whose main sanctuary was at Pessinus in Galatia, various local deity cults, and the increasingly pervasive emperor cult. These were the "gods that by nature are not gods" (<em>tois physei mē ousin theois</em>) — the <em>physei</em> (by nature) directly answers the claim that these deities had genuine divine ontology; Paul denies it categorically.</p>',
    "9": '<p>"But now that you know God — or rather, are known by God — how is it that you are turning back to the weak and beggarly elemental forces?" The correction from "you know God" to "you are known by God" (<em>gnōsthentes hypo theou</em>) reflects the OT concept of divine election as the foundation of knowing (Amos 3:2; Jer 1:5; cf. Gal 1:15-16 on Paul\'s own divine foreknowing). <em>Ptōcha stoicheia</em> (poor/beggarly elemental forces) — the social diminishment language: the elemental forces are not only weak but impoverished, without the resources to give what they promise.</p>',
    "10": '<p>"You are observing days and months and seasons and years" (<em>hēmeras pararatēisthe kai mēnas kai kairous kai eniautous</em>) — the calendar observances Paul identifies could be either Jewish (Sabbath, new moon, annual feasts — Col 2:16 uses the same list in a similar context) or Gentile religious calendar observances, or (most likely in Galatia) the syncretistic combination of both. The agitators who were urging circumcision were likely also introducing Jewish festival observance as part of the full Torah-keeping package. The <em>pararatēomai</em> (to observe carefully, keep watch over) suggests the scrupulous attention characteristic of religious calendar observance in both Jewish and pagan contexts.</p>',
    "11": '<p>Paul\'s fear that he has "labored over you in vain" (<em>eikē kekopiaka eis hymas</em>) is the same fear he expressed about his entire mission in the apostolic-independence argument of 2:2 (<em>mē pōs eis kenon trechō ē edramon</em>). The labor (<em>kopos</em>) language describes the exhausting, costly work of missionary activity; the fear of vain labor is the missionary\'s deepest anxiety — that the community built through costly effort will dissolve. This is Paul\'s pastoral anguish behind the sharp polemical tone of the letter.</p>',
    "12": '<p>"Become as I am, for I also have become as you are" (<em>ginesthe hōs egō, hoti kagō hōs hymeis</em>) is Paul\'s appeal to personal identification. He had become as a Gentile (abandoning the law-keeping that marked his Jewish identity) for the sake of the Gentile mission (1 Cor 9:21); now he appeals to the Galatians to become as he is — free from law-compulsion. The appeal from personal example and mutual relationship breaks the polemical tone momentarily, reminding the Galatians of the genuine affection in the relationship.</p>',
    "13": '<p>Paul\'s "illness of the flesh" (<em>astheneian tēs sarkos</em>) during his initial visit to Galatia has generated extensive speculation: eye disease (the Galatians\' willingness to give their eyes, v15), epilepsy, malaria contracted in the lowland coastal regions and prompting a retreat to the Galatian highlands, or the residual effects of his Lystra stoning (Acts 14:19). The reference establishes that the initial Galatian mission was not Paul\'s original plan but providential — the illness forced an extended stay that became the founding of the Galatian churches. The human weakness became the occasion of the gospel\'s arrival.</p>',
    "14": '<p>"Though my condition was a trial to you, you did not treat me with contempt or scorn" (<em>ton peirasmon hymōn en tē sarki mou ouk exouthenēsate oude exeptysate</em>) — <em>exptyō</em> (to spit out, spit at) was a gesture of contempt in antiquity, used to ward off evil or express disgust at something unclean (Pliny, Natural History 28.35-38 mentions ritual spitting; cf. Num 12:14 where God commands a ritual of disgrace for Miriam). The Galatians had done the opposite: received Paul "as an angel of God, as Christ Jesus himself" — the superlative honor that now contrasts painfully with their current threatened departure from his gospel.</p>',
    "15": '<p>The Galatians\' willingness to "have gouged out your eyes and given them to me" (<em>tous ophthalmous hymōn exoryxantes edōkate moi</em>) is either a hyperbolic expression of extreme generosity (the most precious physical gift imaginable) or a specific reference to Paul\'s eye disease as the condition they would have cured if possible. In the ancient world, eye diseases were among the most feared afflictions; blindness was associated with divine judgment (the blinding of Paul at his conversion, Acts 9:8-9; cf. the Galatian opponents facing blinding judgment in 5:12). The eye-gift hyperbole expresses the depth of the Galatians\' original love for Paul.</p>',
    "16": '<p>"Have I now become your enemy by telling you the truth?" (<em>ēchthos hymōn gegonam alētheōn hymin</em>) — the social dynamic of truth-telling and relationship in ancient Mediterranean culture made the person who delivered unwelcome truth a social enemy rather than a friend. The rhetoric of flattery (<em>kolakeia</em>) was the alternative: saying what the audience wanted to hear to maintain the relationship. Paul\'s choice of truth over flattery — addressed explicitly in v17 (the opponents who "court" the Galatians) — puts him at risk of losing the relationship he had built with the Galatian communities.</p>',
    "17": '<p>"They are zealously pursuing you for no good purpose; they want to isolate you from us so that you will be zealous for them" (<em>zēlousin hymas ou kalōs, alla ekkleisai hymas thelōsin, hina autous zēloute</em>) — the agitators\' technique is described as creating dependency by isolation: separating the Galatians from Paul\'s influence so that the Galatians will direct their zeal toward the agitators. This is recognizable as a technique of social manipulation — creating in-group exclusivity by undermining other relationships. The use of <em>zēloō</em> (to be zealous) in the factional sense anticipates the "works of the flesh" list in 5:20 where "jealousy" (<em>zēlos</em>) appears alongside "factions" and "dissensions."</p>',
    "18": '<p>The good thing "always and not only when I am present with you" (<em>en tō pareinai me pros hymas</em>) points to the problem of the Galatians\' relationship with Paul being distorted by his absence. Ancient letter-writing theory (Cicero, Quintilian) discussed the gap between the letter and the present speaker; Paul\'s letters consistently address the problem that his absent voice is less authoritative than the present voices of opponents. The Galatian situation illustrates this: in Paul\'s presence the communities were stable; in his absence they became vulnerable to different teaching.</p>',
    "19": '<p>"My dear children, for whom I am again in the pains of childbirth until Christ is formed in you" (<em>tekna mou, hous palin ōdinō mechris hou morphōthē Christos en hymin</em>) — the birth-pang metaphor (<em>ōdinō</em>, same word as Rom 8:22) applied to Paul\'s apostolic suffering over the Galatians is unusual in inverting the normal gender associations of the metaphor: Paul takes the role of the laboring mother. The apostle\'s ministry is gendered female in its painful, generative character. <em>Morphōthē Christos en hymin</em> (Christ is formed in you) — the formation of Christ in the community\'s inner life is the goal of the apostolic birth-pangs; it is a gestational image, suggesting a process not yet complete.</p>',
    "20": '<p>"I wish I could be present with you now and change my tone" (<em>ēthelon pareinai pros hymas arti kai allaxai tēn phōnēn mou</em>) — the desire for personal presence over epistolary distance reflects the ancient understanding that the written word was necessarily inferior to the spoken word. Cicero (Letters to Atticus) and Seneca (Letters) both acknowledge the gap between letter and presence; Paul\'s letters consistently acknowledge this gap while insisting that the written word has apostolic authority. The change of tone Paul wishes for would be something between the anguished rebuke of the letter and the personal warmth of direct encounter.</p>',
    "21": '<p>"Tell me, you who want to be under the law: do you not hear the law?" — Paul\'s rhetorical turn to the law-wanting Galatians addresses those who wish to come under the Torah\'s authority. The double meaning of "hear the law" (<em>ton nomon ouk akouete</em>) — hearing it as an audible reading and hearing it as truly understanding its message — is Paul\'s transition to the Sarah-Hagar allegory. The implication: those who truly hear the law\'s deeper message will find in it not an argument for circumcision-requirement but an argument for freedom from that requirement.</p>',
    "22": '<p>The Genesis narrative of Abraham\'s two sons (Gen 16, 21) was a standard text in Jewish interpretation, used to establish various points about covenant membership and spiritual descent. Philo of Alexandria used the Hagar-Sarah narrative allegorically (On Sobriety 7-12; On the Cherubim 3; Who is the Heir? 268) to describe the conflict between earthly and heavenly wisdom. Paul\'s use follows a similar allegorical method but inverts the typical Jewish application: where Jewish interpretation naturally identified with Sarah\'s son as the covenant child, Paul identifies the law-followers with the Hagar-line and the faith-followers with the Sarah-line.</p>',
    "23": '<p>"But the son of the slave was born according to the flesh, while the son of the free woman was born through the promise" — the distinction between birth-by-natural-means and birth-by-promise is Paul\'s hermeneutical key. Ishmael was conceived through Hagar by Abraham\'s own initiative (Gen 16:2-4), without divine promise or miraculous intervention; Isaac was conceived through Sarah in fulfillment of the divine promise and by divine power overcoming biological impossibility (Gen 18:9-15; 21:1-3). The natural/promise distinction maps onto the law/gospel distinction: the law operates in the domain of human capacity and effort; the promise operates in the domain of divine grace and power.</p>',
    "24": '<p>"These things are being allegorized" (<em>hatina estin allēgoroumena</em>) — Paul\'s use of the term <em>allēgoreō</em> (to speak allegorically, to interpret allegorically) is the only NT use of this word, though the method is practiced throughout the NT. The Jewish allegorical tradition (Philo being the most extensive practitioner) read the OT narratives as vehicles for deeper spiritual or philosophical truths. Paul\'s allegorical reading is typological rather than philosophical: he does not evacuate the historical narrative of significance but reads the historical events as patterns that correspond to new-covenant realities. The two women = two covenants reading is the key allegorical equation.</p>',
    "25": '<p>"Now Hagar is Mount Sinai in Arabia and corresponds to the present Jerusalem" (<em>to de Hagar Sina oros estin en tē Arabia, systoichei de tē nyn Ierousalēm</em>) — the identification of Hagar with Sinai is geographically and etymologically argued: (a) Sinai is located in Arabia (the region where Hagar fled and where Paul spent time after his conversion, 1:17); (b) the name "Hagar" may correspond to an Arabic word for "stone" or may be connected to the Arabic name for the Sinai area. The equation Hagar = Sinai = present Jerusalem is the allegory\'s provocative move: Jerusalem, the holy city, is identified with the slave-woman\'s covenant, because the Jerusalem that has not accepted the Messiah\'s gospel is still under the law\'s regime.</p>',
    "26": '<p>"But the Jerusalem that is above is free, and she is our mother" (<em>hē de anō Ierousalēm eleuthera estin, hētis estin mētēr hēmōn</em>) — the heavenly Jerusalem was a developed concept in Jewish apocalyptic. 4 Ezra 7:26 and 10:27 describe the heavenly Jerusalem as the true city that will be revealed at the eschaton. 2 Baruch 4:3-7 records God telling Baruch that the Jerusalem he saw was "not this building that is in your midst now" but the heavenly one shown to Adam, Abraham, and Moses. Hebrews 12:22-24 uses the same tradition. Paul identifies the new covenant community as belonging to the heavenly city rather than the earthly one that is under the law\'s jurisdiction.</p>',
    "27": '<p>Isaiah 54:1 is cited from the LXX: "Rejoice, you barren woman who bears no children; shout and cry out, you who have no birth pains; because the children of the desolate woman will be more numerous than those of the woman who has a husband." In its original context, Isa 54 follows the fourth Servant Song (Isa 52:13-53:12) and addresses Israel in exile as the barren woman who will be restored. Paul applies it to Sarah (the previously barren woman) and through her to the new covenant community (the "Jerusalem above"): the children of the free woman — the faith-community — are the fulfillment of Isaiah\'s vision of the restored people who exceed the children of the law-covenant.</p>',
    "28": '<p>"Now you, brothers and sisters, like Isaac, are children of promise" (<em>hymeis de, adelphoi, kata Isaak epangelias tekna este</em>) — the Galatians\' identity is located in the Isaac-line: children of the promise, born through the Spirit\'s power rather than human effort. The "like Isaac" (<em>kata Isaak</em>) is the typological identification: as Isaac was born through the divine promise overcoming human impossibility, so the new covenant community is constituted by the Spirit\'s creative power (3:2-5), not by the flesh\'s efforts at law-keeping.</p>',
    "29": '<p>"At that time the one born according to the flesh persecuted the one born according to the Spirit; so it is also now" (<em>hōsper tote ho kata sarka gennētheis ediōken ton kata pneuma, houtōs kai nyn</em>) — the "persecution" of Isaac by Ishmael is inferred from Gen 21:9 (where Ishmael "mocked" or "played with" Isaac — the MT uses <em>metzahek</em>, which can mean mocking). Jewish midrash elaborated this as actual physical persecution (Gen. Rabbah 53:11 interprets the term as including idolatry, sexual immorality, and bloodshed). Paul\'s "so it is also now" draws a direct parallel: the agitators who are compelling circumcision are enacting the Ishmael-role toward the Isaac-community.</p>',
    "30": '<p>"What does the Scripture say? Drive out the slave and her son; for the son of the slave will not inherit with the son of the free woman" (<em>ekbale tēn paidiskēn kai ton huion autēs</em>) — Paul cites Gen 21:10 (Sarah\'s words to Abraham confirmed by God in v12) as Scripture\'s own directive regarding the incompatibility of the two covenants in the one household. The verb <em>ekballō</em> (to drive out, expel) is strong; this is not a gentle separation but a decisive expulsion. Paul\'s application implies that the law-covenant cannot coexist with the faith-covenant as co-equal paths to the inheritance: one must be chosen.</p>',
    "31": '<p>"So then, brothers and sisters, we are not children of the slave but of the free woman" (<em>hēmeis adelphoi, ouk esmen paidiskēs tekna alla tēs eleutheras</em>) — the conclusion of the allegory returns to the community\'s identity: they are Sarah-children, free-woman children, promise-children. The "so then" (<em>ara</em>) draws out the consequence for their present situation: the identity-truth is the motivation for the freedom-claim that opens ch5. The community\'s understanding of who they are (free children of the promise) determines how they respond to the pressure to submit to circumcision (a return to the Hagar-line).'
  },
  "5": {
    "1": '<p>"It is for freedom that Christ has set us free. Stand firm, then, and do not let yourselves be burdened again by a yoke of slavery" (<em>tē eleutheria hēmas Christos ēleutherōsen; stēkete oun kai mē palin zygō douleias enechesthe</em>) — the "yoke of slavery" (<em>zygō douleias</em>) was a recognized Jewish metaphor for Torah-observance: the rabbis spoke of "taking on the yoke of Torah" and "the yoke of the kingdom of heaven" (m. Avot 3:5). To accept circumcision and law-keeping was to take on the yoke that Peter himself described as a burden "which neither our ancestors nor we have been able to bear" (Acts 15:10). The freedom Paul declares is freedom from this yoke — not lawlessness but a different form of governance.</p>',
    "2": '<p>"Mark my words! I, Paul, tell you that if you let yourselves be circumcised, Christ will be of no value to you at all" (<em>ide egō Paulos legō hymin hoti ean peritemnesthe, Christos hymas ouden ōphelēsei</em>) — Paul\'s personal emphasis (<em>egō Paulos</em>) frames this as his direct apostolic voice, the most authoritative form of communication available in a letter. The theological claim about circumcision\'s effect on Christ\'s value is stark: circumcision as a means of justification places one outside the realm where Christ\'s death functions as justification. The two systems (law-righteousness through circumcision and grace-righteousness through Christ) are mutually exclusive as grounds of standing before God.</p>',
    "3": '<p>"Again I declare to every man who lets himself be circumcised that he is obligated to obey the whole law" (<em>opheiletēs estin holon ton nomon poiēsai</em>) — the obligation incurred by circumcision is total: the one who undergoes circumcision as a religious act is taking on the entire law-covenant package (Exod 24:7; Deut 27:26 — cf. Gal 3:10). This was the standard Jewish understanding: circumcision was the entry-point into the covenant that required Torah-keeping in all its dimensions. Paul\'s point is that the agitators who urge circumcision may not have fully disclosed this total obligation to their potential converts.</p>',
    "4": '<p>"You who are trying to be justified by the law have been alienated from Christ; you have fallen away from grace" (<em>katērgēthēte apo Christou, hoitines en nomō dikaiousthai zēteite, tēs charitos exepesate</em>) — "fallen away from grace" (<em>tēs charitos exepesate</em>) became a standard phrase in later theological debate about apostasy and perseverance. In Paul\'s context, the "falling" is not from salvation but from the grace-principle as the basis of justification: to seek law-justification is to exit the domain in which grace operates. <em>Ekpiptō</em> (to fall out of, fall from) is an athletic and nautical term — falling off the track or falling off-course from the destination.</p>',
    "5": '<p>"For through the Spirit, by faith, we eagerly await the righteousness for which we hope" (<em>hēmeis gar pneumati ek pisteōs elpida dikaiosynēs apekdechometha</em>) — the eschatological dimension of justification: the "righteousness" here is the final verdict at the last judgment, awaited by those who already possess it by faith in the present. The same <em>apekdechomai</em> (eagerly await with outstretched neck) as in Rom 8:19 and 23; the Spirit-given hope is of a quality similar to creation\'s own eager watching. The Spirit, faith, and hope are the three-fold gift of the present age that orients the community toward the eschatological completion.</p>',
    "6": '<p>"For in Christ Jesus neither circumcision nor uncircumcision has any value. The only thing that counts is faith expressing itself through love" (<em>pistis di\' agapēs energoumenē</em>) — <em>energeoumenē</em> (present passive or middle participle of <em>energeō</em>) — "faith being made effective through love" or "faith working through love." This phrase became the center of the Catholic-Protestant debate in the Reformation: Luther\'s "faith alone" vs. the Council of Trent\'s insistence on love as the form of faith. For Paul, the phrase describes the organic connection between faith (the root) and love (the expression): faith that does not love is inert, but love that is not grounded in faith is moralism.</p>',
    "7": '<p>"You were running a good race. Who cut in on you to keep you from obeying the truth?" (<em>tis hymas enekopsen alētheia mē peithesthai</em>) — the athletic metaphor of running well (<em>kalos etrechete</em>) echoes 2:2 (the fear of running in vain) and 5:1 (standing firm). The sabotage-vocabulary <em>enkoptō</em> (to cut in, hinder, block the path) was used for obstacles placed on roads and for the military tactic of cutting the enemy\'s advance. Someone (the agitators — the specific identity left deliberate vague) has cut across the Galatians\' path and diverted them from the truth-course they were running.</p>',
    "8": '<p>"That kind of persuasion does not come from the one who calls you" (<em>hē peismonē ouk ek tou kalountos hymas</em>) — the word <em>peismonē</em> (persuasion) is a hapax legomenon in the NT, possibly coined or chosen deliberately by Paul. It plays on the wordplay with "you were persuaded" (form of <em>peithō</em>) in v7: the persuasion that has led them astray does not have the character of the divine calling. The criterion: legitimate teaching produces receptivity toward the gospel; false teaching produces resistance to it — the test is not the teacher\'s credentials alone but whether their message aligns with the one who called.</p>',
    "9": '<p>"A little yeast works through the whole batch of dough" (<em>mikra zymē holon to phyrama zymoi</em>) — the yeast proverb is used by Paul also in 1 Corinthians 5:6 (in the context of the immoral man who was tolerated in the Corinthian community). The point: false teaching spreads by its own internal logic, requiring only a small initial entry to permeate the whole. The Passover-Unleavened Bread context of yeast as contamination (Exod 12:15-20; 13:7; 1 Cor 5:7-8) may be in view: the new Passover community should be free of the old leaven of law-righteousness.</p>',
    "10": '<p>"I am confident in the Lord that you will take no other view" (<em>egō pepoitha eis hymas en kyriō hoti ouden allo phronēsete</em>) — the <em>phroneo</em> (mindset) vocabulary returns: Paul is confident the Galatians will adopt the right mindset in Christ rather than the competing mindset offered by the agitators. "The one who is throwing you into confusion, whoever that may be, will pay the penalty" (<em>o de tarassōn hymas bastasei to krima, hostis an ē</em>) — the indefinite <em>hostis an ē</em> (whoever that may be) is deliberately non-specific, possibly targeting the agitators\' patron or leader whose identity Paul either does not know or chooses not to specify.</p>',
    "11": '<p>"Brothers and sisters, if I am still preaching circumcision, why am I still being persecuted? In that case the offense of the cross has been abolished" (<em>ei peritmēn eti kēryssō, ti eti diōkomai; ara katērgētai to skandalon tou staurou</em>) — Paul may be responding to the agitators\' claim that he himself preached circumcision in certain contexts (perhaps referring to his circumcision of Timothy, Acts 16:3, or his vow in Acts 18:18). The refutation: if he were preaching circumcision, he would not be persecuted — the persecution itself is evidence that his gospel offends the circumcision-advocates. The "offense of the cross" (<em>skandalon tou staurou</em>) is the cross\'s incompatibility with the human pride in religious achievement that circumcision represents.</p>',
    "12": '<p>"As for those agitators, I wish they would go the whole way and emasculate themselves!" (<em>Ophelon kai apokopsontai hoi anastatountes hymas</em>) — <em>apokoptō</em> (to cut off, castrate) — Paul\'s most shocking statement in the letter; the phrase refers to self-castration as practiced by priests of Cybele (the Great Mother, whose cult was centered in Galatia at Pessinus). The priests of Cybele underwent ritual castration as a devotion to the goddess. Paul\'s irony is directed at the circumcision-advocates: if a little cutting is good, why not go all the way and castrate themselves in the Cybele-tradition? The comparison of circumcision-advocacy to pagan devotional mutilation is deliberately provocative and offensive to Jewish sensibilities.</p>',
    "13": '<p>"You, my brothers and sisters, were called to be free. But do not use your freedom to indulge the flesh; rather, serve one another humbly in love" (<em>mē tēn eleutherian eis aphormen tē sarki, alla dia tēs agapēs douleuete allēlois</em>) — <em>aphormē</em> (base of operations, starting point for an attack) — freedom is not to be used as a beachhead for fleshly indulgence, which would undermine the community Paul is defending. The Stoic philosophers also discussed freedom and the danger of licentiousness: Epictetus (Discourses 2.1.23) warned against the person who claims freedom but is enslaved to desires. Paul\'s solution is not law-restraint but love-service: the freedom that serves another in love is the fulfilled freedom.</p>',
    "14": '<p>The summary of the entire law in Leviticus 19:18 ("love your neighbor as yourself") echoes Jesus\'s own teaching (Mark 12:31; Matt 22:39; Luke 10:27) and aligns with both the Hillel tradition and the Johannine tradition. Galatians 5:14 is one of three places Paul uses the love-neighbor summary (cf. Rom 13:9; 1 Cor 13). The use of the perfect passive <em>peplērōtai</em> (has been fulfilled) rather than a command to fulfill suggests that this is a description of what love accomplishes, not merely what it is commanded to do: love does not merely attempt to fulfill the law but actually accomplishes it.</p>',
    "15": '<p>"If you bite and devour each other, watch out or you will be destroyed by each other" (<em>ei de allēlous daknete kai katesthiete, blepete mē hyp\' allēlōn analōthēte</em>) — the animal-imagery of biting (<em>daknō</em>) and devouring (<em>katesthiō</em>) describes community conflict in visceral terms. The warning is that theological disputes, when conducted with the weapons of personal attack and character destruction, produce the same result as the faction and division that the law was supposed to prevent — and do so to the destroyers as much as to the destroyed.</p>',
    "16": '<p>"Walk by the Spirit, and you will not gratify the desires of the flesh" (<em>pneumati stoicheite kai epithumian sarkos ou mē telesēte</em>) — the imperative to "walk by the Spirit" (<em>pneumati stoicheite</em> — literally: walk in line with the Spirit) uses the same military-formation verb <em>stoicheō</em> as in 6:16 ("walk by this rule") and Phil 3:16. The negative result (not gratifying fleshly desires) follows as a consequence of Spirit-walking rather than as the primary goal; the primary command is Spirit-alignment, not sin-avoidance. The Stoic <em>akolouthia</em> (following nature/reason) provides the background, recast with the Spirit as the reality that nature and reason only imperfectly pointed toward.</p>',
    "17": '<p>"For the flesh desires what is contrary to the Spirit, and the Spirit what is contrary to the flesh. They are in conflict with each other, so that you are not to do whatever you want" (<em>he gar sarx epithumei kata tou pneumatos, to de pneuma kata tēs sarkos; tauta gar allēlois antikeitai, hina mē ha ean thelēte tauta poiēte</em>) — the conflict between flesh and Spirit describes the experienced moral condition of the believer in the overlapping of the ages: the new Spirit-life exists within the old flesh-reality, creating the inner conflict Paul describes more extensively in Romans 7:14-25. The phrase "so that you do not do what you want" may mean that the conflict prevents believers from doing the evil they want (the Spirit restrains the flesh) and also prevents them from doing all the good they want (the flesh restrains the Spirit).</p>',
    "18": '<p>"But if you are led by the Spirit, you are not under the law" (<em>ei de pneumati agesthe, ouk este hypo nomon</em>) — the Spirit-leading that characterizes the children of God (Rom 8:14) is the alternative to law-governance. Being "under the law" in Paul means being under its juridical claim and condemnation; Spirit-led people are not under that claim because they are not seeking law-righteousness. The Spirit does not abolish the law\'s ethical content but transforms the means of fulfilling it from external compulsion to internal movement.</p>',
    "19": '<p>The "works of the flesh" (<em>erga tēs sarkos</em>) list in vv19-21 is one of several virtue-and-vice catalogs in Paul (cf. Rom 1:29-31; 1 Cor 6:9-10; 2 Cor 12:20-21; Col 3:5-9; 1 Tim 1:9-10). Such catalogs were a common feature of Hellenistic moral philosophy (Stoic, Peripatetic, and popular ethics) and of Jewish ethical instruction (Wisdom of Solomon 14:25-26; 2 Enoch 10:4-6; T. Reuben 3:2-6). Paul\'s list covers four categories: sexual (fornication, impurity, debauchery), religious (idolatry, witchcraft), relational (hatred, discord, jealousy, rage, self-seeking, dissensions, factions, envy), and physical excess (drunkenness, carousing).</p>',
    "20": '<p>The relational vices in the flesh-list (<em>echthai, eris, zēlos, thymos, eritheiai, dichostasiai, haireseis, phthonoi</em> — hatred, discord, jealousy, fits of rage, self-seeking ambitions, dissensions, factions, envy) are particularly relevant to the Galatian situation, where the community is being torn apart by the circumcision controversy. The word <em>haireseis</em> (factions, heresies — from <em>haireō</em> = to choose) is here in the sense of party-forming rather than doctrinal deviation; the factional spirit is itself a work of the flesh regardless of the theological trigger for the faction.</p>',
    "21": '<p>"I warn you, as I did before, that those who live like this will not inherit the kingdom of God" (<em>prolegō hymin, kathōs proeipon, hoti hoi ta toiauta prassontes basileian theou ou klēronomēsousin</em>) — the "as I did before" indicates an oral warning Paul had given during his initial Galatian visit; the letter reinforces what was already taught. <em>Basileian theou ou klēronomēsousin</em> (will not inherit the kingdom of God) — this is eschatological exclusion: those who practice the flesh-works as a lifestyle pattern are excluded from the inheritance. The parallel with the baptismal confession "the unrighteous will not inherit the kingdom" (1 Cor 6:9-10) suggests this was standard early Christian catechetical content.</p>',
    "22": '<p>The "fruit of the Spirit" (<em>karpos tou pneumatos</em>) is singular — one fruit with nine characteristics — contrasting with the plural "works of the flesh." The unity of the fruit reflects the unity of its source (the Spirit), while the diversity of its expressions reflects the fullness of love that produces all the other characteristics. The nine characteristics (love, joy, peace, patience, kindness, goodness, faithfulness, gentleness, self-control) correspond to the Stoic list of virtues but differ in grounding: Stoic virtues are achieved through reason and discipline; the Spirit\'s fruit is received through union with Christ and the Spirit\'s work.</p>',
    "23": '<p>"Against such things there is no law" (<em>kata tōn toioutōn ouk estin nomos</em>) — the fruit of the Spirit generates a life that no law can condemn; the law has no jurisdiction over the Spirit-produced life because the Spirit accomplishes what the law demanded but could not produce. This is Paul\'s ironic reversal of the law-freedom debate: those who seek freedom through law-observance are ironically more constrained by the law\'s condemnation of their failures; those who walk in the Spirit are truly free from the law\'s jurisdiction because the Spirit produces the law\'s goal.</p>',
    "24": '<p>"Those who belong to Christ Jesus have crucified the flesh with its passions and desires" (<em>hoi de tou Christou Iēsou tēn sarka estaurōsan syn tois pathēmasin kai tais epithymiais</em>) — the aorist <em>estaurōsan</em> (they crucified) points to the historical moment of conversion/baptism as the act of co-crucifixion with Christ (cf. 2:19-20: "I have been crucified with Christ"). The crucifixion of the flesh\'s passions is both a past event (at conversion) and a present practice (the ongoing mortification that flows from the past event). The flesh does not simply die at conversion but its death-sentence was enacted at that point, with the execution implemented through the Spirit\'s ongoing work.</p>',
    "25": '<p>"Since we live by the Spirit, let us keep in step with the Spirit" (<em>ei zōmen pneumati, pneumati kai stoichōmen</em>) — the indicative (<em>zōmen</em> = we live) precedes the imperative (<em>stoichōmen</em> = let us walk in line with). The ethical imperative is grounded in the soteriological indicative: because the Spirit is already the source of the believer\'s life, the appropriate response is to align the whole lifestyle with the Spirit\'s guidance. The military-formation image of <em>stoicheō</em> suggests not mere individual moral improvement but coordinated community movement in the Spirit\'s direction.</p>',
    "26": '<p>"Let us not become conceited, provoking and envying each other" (<em>mē ginōmetha kenodoxoi, allēlous prokaloumenoi, allēlois phthonountes</em>) — <em>kenodoxia</em> (empty glory, vainglory) is the antithesis of the cross-shaped humility that Paul has commended throughout the letter. The two relational vices (<em>prokaleō</em> = to challenge or provoke to combat; <em>phthoneō</em> = to envy, to desire what another has) are the typical results of <em>kenodoxia</em>: the person who seeks vain glory either attacks others (provocation) or resents their successes (envy). Both are works of the flesh (v20: <em>eris, zēlos, phthonos</em>) expressed in the community\'s internal life.</p>'
  },
  "6": {
    "1": '<p>"Brothers and sisters, if someone is caught in a sin, you who live by the Spirit should restore that person gently" (<em>oi pneumatikoi katartizete ton toiouton en pneumati praytētos</em>) — <em>katartizō</em> (to restore, repair, mend, put right) is a medical term for setting a broken bone and a fishing term for mending nets (Matt 4:21). The community has a responsibility to restore the fallen with the same care that a physician or craftsman applies to repairing something broken — gently and with expertise. <em>Katartizete</em> (present active imperative: keep restoring, be in the practice of restoring) indicates this is an ongoing community function, not a one-time emergency response.</p>',
    "2": '<p>"Carry each other\'s burdens, and in this way you will fulfill the law of Christ" (<em>allēlōn ta barē bastazete kai houtōs anaplērōsete ton nomon tou Christou</em>) — <em>baros</em> (burden, weight) — the physical weight of a heavy load; the community\'s mutual burden-bearing is the practical expression of love that fulfills "the law of Christ" (the love-command of John 13:34-35; 15:12). The "law of Christ" is both a reference to Jesus\'s specific commandments and to the entire pattern of his self-giving life as the regulative principle for community ethics. The contrast with the "law of Moses" being argued throughout the letter is pointed: the law that truly matters for the new-covenant community is the law of Christ.</p>',
    "3": '<p>"If anyone thinks they are something when they are not, they deceive themselves" (<em>ei gar dokei tis einai ti mēden ōn, phrenapata heauton</em>) — <em>phrenapataō</em> (to deceive the mind, delude oneself) — a compound found only here in the NT. The self-deception of the person who overestimates their spiritual status is the root of the failure to bear others\' burdens: the one who considers themselves exceptional does not need to share the common human load. The Galatian agitators who consider themselves spiritually superior (having the full law-keeping that the Gentile converts lack) exemplify this self-deception.</p>',
    "4": '<p>"Each one should test their own actions. Then they can take pride in themselves alone, without comparing themselves to someone else" (<em>to de ergon heautou dokimazeto hekastos, kai tote eis heauton monon to kauchēma exei kai ouk eis ton heteron</em>) — <em>dokimazō</em> (to test, examine, prove) — the same testing/approval language as Romans 12:2 and 1 Corinthians 11:28; self-examination rather than competitive self-comparison is the appropriate mode of moral assessment. The boast (<em>kauchēma</em>) that comes from genuine self-examination is not comparative pride but the legitimate satisfaction of genuine work done well.</p>',
    "5": '<p>"For each one should carry their own load" (<em>hekastos gar to idion phortion bastasei</em>) — <em>phortion</em> (pack, load, burden) is a different word from <em>baros</em> (v2 — the excess weight): <em>phortion</em> is the normal load that a person carries as their own responsibility (a soldier\'s pack, a traveler\'s bag). Paul is not contradicting v2 but distinguishing: the community bears one another\'s excess burdens while each person carries their own normal load of responsibility. The eschatological note in the future tense (<em>bastasei</em> = will carry) may hint at the last judgment at which each will account for their own actions (v5 in context of vv4-5).</p>',
    "6": '<p>"Nevertheless, the one who receives instruction in the word should share all good things with their instructor" (<em>koinōneitō de ho katēchoumenos ton logon tō katēchounti en pasin agathois</em>) — <em>katēchoumai</em> (to be taught, receive oral instruction — the root of "catechism") and <em>katēcheō</em> (to instruct, teach) describe the formal teacher-learner relationship. The instruction in the word was likely done through a teacher designated for this purpose in the community. The financial support of teachers was not universal in ancient culture: Stoic philosophers often taught freely, while Sophists charged fees. The early church developed its own norms for teacher-support, reflected here and in 1 Cor 9:14; 1 Tim 5:17-18.</p>',
    "7": '<p>"Do not be deceived: God cannot be mocked. A man reaps what he sows" (<em>mē planasthe, theos ou myktērizetai; ho gar ean speirē anthrōpos, touto kai therisei</em>) — <em>myktērizō</em> (to turn up the nose at, mock, treat with contempt) — a hapax legomenon in the NT. The agricultural proverb of sowing and reaping appears in widely distributed ancient literature (Job 4:8; Prov 22:8; Hos 8:7; 2 Cor 9:6) but is here applied specifically to the moral-spiritual domain: what one sows to (flesh or Spirit) determines what kind of harvest one will reap. The proverb grounds the coming warning about the eternal consequences of lifestyle orientation.</p>',
    "8": '<p>"Whoever sows to please their flesh, from the flesh will reap destruction; whoever sows to please the Spirit, from the Spirit will reap eternal life" (<em>ho speirōn eis tēn sarka heautou ek tēs sarkos therisei phthoran; ho de speirōn eis to pneuma ek tou pneumatos therisei zōēn aiōnion</em>) — <em>phthora</em> (destruction, decay, corruption) and <em>zōē aiōnios</em> (eternal life) are the eschatological harvest of the two different sowings. The present tenses of sowing (<em>speirōn</em>) and the future tense of reaping (<em>therisei</em>) maintain the temporal structure: the sowing is present; the harvest is future. The flesh-to-corruption connection reflects the Adamic mortality that the flesh-orientation perpetuates; the Spirit-to-life connection reflects the resurrection-life that the Spirit inaugurates.</p>',
    "9": '<p>"Let us not become weary in doing good, for at the proper time we will reap a harvest if we do not give up" (<em>to de kalon poiountes mē ekkakōmen; kairō gar idiō therisomen mē eklyomenoi</em>) — <em>ekkakeō</em> (to grow weary, lose heart) and <em>eklyō</em> (to be exhausted, lose strength) describe the fatigue of sustained ethical effort. The "proper time" (<em>kairō idiō</em>) is the eschatological moment of harvest — the final judgment at which the sowing of good deeds will be rewarded. The patience required to wait for the harvest without giving up is the same patience (hypomonē) that Paul commends elsewhere in contexts of eschatological hope (Rom 5:3-4; 8:25).</p>',
    "10": '<p>"Therefore, as we have opportunity, let us do good to all people, especially to those who belong to the family of believers" (<em>hōs kairon echomen, ergazōmetha to agathon pros pantas, malista de pros tous oikeious tēs pisteōs</em>) — <em>oikeious tēs pisteōs</em> (household of faith, domestic members of the faith) — the community as a household (<em>oikos</em>) defined by shared faith rather than blood kinship. The priority of the faith-household in community care does not exclude outsiders but establishes the primary community of obligation while extending good to all. The "as we have opportunity" (<em>hōs kairon echomen</em>) introduces the kairos-concept of appropriate, well-timed action.</p>',
    "11": '<p>"See what large letters I use as I write to you with my own hand!" (<em>idete pēlikois hymin grammasin egrapsa tē emē cheiri</em>) — the size of Paul\'s writing (<em>pēlikois grammasin</em>) has been debated: (a) a sign of genuine physical eye-trouble that made small writing difficult (connecting to 4:15); (b) the ordinary "large hand" of someone not professionally trained as a scribe; (c) a deliberate emphasis marking the personal importance of the concluding section. Letters in antiquity were typically dictated to an amanuensis (secretary) and then the author would add a closing greeting in their own hand to authenticate the letter (cf. 1 Cor 16:21; Col 4:18; 2 Thess 3:17).</p>',
    "12": '<p>"Those who want to impress people by means of the flesh are trying to compel you to be circumcised. The only reason they do this is to avoid being persecuted for the cross of Christ" (<em>hosoi theloustin euprosōpēsai en sarki, houtoi anankamzousin hymas peritemnesasthai, monon hina tō staurō tou Christou mē diōkōntai</em>) — <em>euprosōpeō</em> (to make a good show, have a good public face) — the social motivation: the agitators were avoiding persecution from Jewish communities by demonstrating that their Gentile converts were law-observant. A circumcised Gentile community was safe within the Jewish communal structure; an uncircumcised Gentile community following a crucified messianic pretender was religiously and socially exposed.</p>',
    "13": '<p>"Not even those who are circumcised keep the law, yet they want you to be circumcised that they may boast about your flesh" (<em>oude gar hoi peritemnnomenoi autoi nomon phylassousin, alla theloustin hymas peritemnesasthai hina en tē hymetera sarki kauchēsōntai</em>) — Paul\'s charge that the circumcisers do not themselves fully keep the law echoes his criticism of Jewish hypocrisy in Romans 2:17-24: claiming law-devotion while not practicing it. The motive he identifies — boasting in the Galatians\' flesh (their circumcision as the agitators\' achievement) — is the social prestige of a successful circumcision-campaign among formerly uncircumcised Gentile communities.</p>',
    "14": '<p>"May I never boast except in the cross of our Lord Jesus Christ, through which the world has been crucified to me, and I to the world" (<em>emoi de mē genoito kauchasthai ei mē en tō staurō tou kyriou hēmōn Iēsou Christou, di\' hou emoi kosmos estaurōtai kagō kosmō</em>) — Paul\'s counter-boast against the agitators\' boasting in circumcision: his only boast is in the instrument of his Lord\'s shameful death. The cross as the object of boasting was categorically shocking in the Roman world, where crucifixion was the most degrading form of execution reserved for slaves and criminals. The mutual crucifixion of Paul to the world and the world to Paul describes the radical social dislocation that results from the cross becoming one\'s primary allegiance.</p>',
    "15": '<p>"Neither circumcision nor uncircumcision means anything; what counts is the new creation" (<em>oute gar peritomē ti estin oute akrobystia, alla kainē ktisis</em>) — the declaration that the primary religious distinction of the ancient world (Jew/Gentile, circumcised/uncircumcised) is relativized by the category of "new creation" (<em>kainē ktisis</em>) picks up the eschatological theology of 2 Cor 5:17 ("if anyone is in Christ, the new creation has come"). The <em>kainē ktisis</em> is not merely personal renewal but the eschatological new creation of Isa 65:17-25 and 66:22 already inaugurated in the Christ-event. Circumcision and uncircumcision belong to the old creation that is passing away.</p>',
    "16": '<p>"Peace and mercy to all who follow this rule — to the Israel of God" (<em>kai hosoi tō kanoni toutō stoichēsousin, eirēnē ep\' autous kai eleos, kai epi ton Israēl tou theou</em>) — "the Israel of God" (<em>tou Israēl tou theou</em>) is one of the most debated phrases in Galatians. Options: (a) the whole church (Jewish and Gentile believers) = Israel of God (common Protestant interpretation); (b) Jewish believers specifically — the believing remnant within ethnic Israel; (c) future ethnic Israel whose salvation Paul hopes for (cf. Rom 11:26). The grammar (<em>kai epi</em> can be "and also" or simply "and") determines whether this is one group (the <em>kai</em> is epexegetical) or two (all who follow this rule, and also Israel of God).</p>',
    "17": '<p>"From now on, let no one cause me trouble, for I bear on my body the marks of Jesus" (<em>ta stigmata tou Iēsou en tō sōmati mou bastazō</em>) — <em>stigmata</em> (marks, brands) — in the Greco-Roman world, slaves were branded with their owner\'s mark to identify them as property; devotees of certain mystery cults were tattooed to mark their religious allegiance; soldiers bore identification marks. Paul\'s <em>stigmata tou Iēsou</em> are the physical marks left by his sufferings for the gospel: beatings, stonings, imprisonments (2 Cor 11:23-27). These marks on his body are his counter-claim to the circumcision the agitators promote: circumcision marks the flesh with the sign of one master\'s law; Paul\'s scars mark him as belonging to Jesus through suffering.</p>',
    "18": '<p>"The grace of our Lord Jesus Christ be with your spirit, brothers and sisters. Amen." — the closing benediction is the shortest of Paul\'s epistolary conclusions and notably includes "brothers and sisters" (<em>adelphoi</em>) — the family language with which Paul began his emotional appeal in 4:12. Despite the sharp polemic of the letter, Paul closes by claiming the Galatians as his siblings in Christ. The grace-benediction circles back to the opening (1:3: grace to you from God our Father and the Lord Jesus Christ) and to the thesis (2:21: I do not nullify the grace of God): grace is the beginning, the subject, and the ending of the letter\'s argument.</p>'
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'galatians')
    merge_comm(existing, GALATIANS)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'galatians', existing)
    print('Galatians 4–6 mkt-context written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
